url="http://gtr.ukri.org:80/projects?ref=BBS%2FE%2FC%2F00004943"><gtr:id>E9081628-DDFB-4154-8BA6-2E370216B033</gtr:id><gtr:title>Complex spatial variation of environmental variables: sampling, prediction and interpretation</gtr:title><gtr:status>Closed</gtr:status><gtr:grantCategory>Intramural</gtr:grantCategory><gtr:grantReference>BBS/E/C/00004943</gtr:grantReference><gtr:abstractText>The aim of this project is to develop theoretically sound and practically workable and robust methods to allow cost-effective prediction, estimation and scientific interpretation of complex spatial variation. These methods are to be applied to understanding the behaviour of soil systems, and to guide their management. The specific scientific objectives are as follows:

1. To extend and critically assess the linear mixed model framework for spatial analysis of environmental properties to cover complex and non-stationary variables.
2. To develop Bayesian approaches to spatial prediction, with particular emphasis on how this allows us to incorporate process information and use soft data or data of variable quality.
3. To invent methods for spatial analysis based on the wavelet transform, with particular interest in multivariate problems and irregularly sampled data.
4. To tackle the problem of modelling spatio-temporal covariance for complex processes.

Objective 1 will deliver a suite of methods for spatial analysis and prediction, and for optimizing sample design. The methods will also allow us to partition a complex data set into realizations of a background process and of a contaminating process. The methods will be exemplified in case studies with collaborators such as the British Geological Survey and INRA

Objective 2 will deliver an evaluation of an approach to spatial analysis that has attracted much interest but which is thought to have much unrealized potential (particularly with respect to the incorporation of process understanding).

Objective 3 will develop substantial advances in wavelet methodology, allowing these powerful methods to be applied to new data and to new problems (particularly with respect to the characterization of multivariate spatial variation).

Objective 4 will give insight into the complex spatio-temporal variation of some key processes, and how they may best be sampled and predicted.</gtr:abstractText><gtr:fund><gtr:end>2012-03-31</gtr:end><gtr:funder url="http://gtr.ukri.org:80/organisation/2512EF1C-401B-4222-9869-A770D4C5FAC7"><gtr:id>2512EF1C-401B-4222-9869-A770D4C5FAC7</gtr:id><gtr:name>BBSRC</gtr:name></gtr:funder><gtr:start>2008-04-01</gtr:start><gtr:type>EXPENDITURE_PROJECTED</gtr:type><gtr:valuePounds>959081</gtr:valuePounds></gtr:fund><gtr:output><gtr:artisticAndCreativeProductOutputs/><gtr:collaborationOutputs/><gtr:disseminationOutputs/><gtr:exploitationOutputs/><gtr:furtherFundingOutputs/><gtr:impactSummaryOutputs><gtr:impactSummaryOutput><gtr:description>The statistical methods developed in this project have been adopted by other researchers studying a range of environmental systems such as the development of a Global Soil Map, studies of the spatial variation of the response to cereal crops to different fertilizer rates and the mapping of soil inorganic pollutants across France. 

The outcomes of the individual case studies have informed the design of subsequent phases of soil monitoring schemes in both France and the Florida Everglades and the findings have informed policy makers regarding the threats posed by soil contamination.

The study of the use of radiometric data to quantify soil carbon storage has informed DEFRA about the usefulness of remotely sensed data for soil monitoring.</gtr:description><gtr:firstYearOfImpact>2010</gtr:firstYearOfImpact><gtr:id>A8C3EAB1-91D6-4085-9B7F-40B34AF93E6E</gtr:id><gtr:impactTypes><gtr:impactType>Societal,Policy &amp; public services</gtr:impactType></gtr:impactTypes><gtr:outcomeId>5464dcde16dcd1.56732465</gtr:outcomeId><gtr:sector>Agriculture, Food and Drink,Environment</gtr:sector></gtr:impactSummaryOutput></gtr:impactSummaryOutputs><gtr:intellectualPropertyOutputs/><gtr:keyFindingsOutput><gtr:description>This project has developed and expanded a number of statistical methods required to interpret a range of spatial and spatio-temporal datasets. Highlights include:

The extension of adaptive sampling approaches to surveys of soil contamination. These methods update the sample design during the survey to focus on sites where contamination status is most uncertain.

The development of robust geostatistical methods to map and interpret soil properties at the national-scale. In particular, the methods were applied to measurements of soil cadmium accross France and were able to distinguish components due to processes acting over disparate spatial scales.

The use of copulas to map soil properties. This approach is particularly suited to properties that are prone to extreme values. In contrast to standard models, copulas are able to accurately predict the likelihood of multiple extreme values within a small area.

The extension of Bayesian Maximum Entropy methods to map soil properties which include a large proportion of measurements which are less than a detection limit. 

An exploration of the use of areal kriging to produce high resolution maps of soil properties from low resolution classifications of soil type.

An evaluation of the use of airborne gamma radiation data to map soil carbon stocks.

The development of a new model of spatio-temporal variation and its application to identify trends in soil phosphorus contamination in the Florida Everglades.</gtr:description><gtr:exploitationPathways>These ststistical approaches are applicable for the analysis of any environmental property that varies in time and space. The approaches have already been adopted by researchers working in a range of areas. For example, the areal kriging methodology is being used by a consortium funded by the Gates Foundation to produce a Global Soil Map. The robust mapping algorithm is now a standard proceedure used by the French National Soil Monitoring Network. The copula models are being used to model and predict groundwater floods and droughts.</gtr:exploitationPathways><gtr:id>B971C0A5-632B-40A3-B2F0-8394EA55B080</gtr:id><gtr:outcomeId>5464dad2d322e5.88884975</gtr:outcomeId><gtr:sectors><gtr:sector>Agriculture, Food and Drink,Construction,Environment</gtr:sector></gtr:sectors></gtr:keyFindingsOutput><gtr:otherResearchOutputs/><gtr:policyInfluenceOutputs><gtr:policyInfluenceOutput><gtr:areas/><gtr:description>Soil monitoring practice</gtr:description><gtr:geographicReach>Multiple continents/international</gtr:geographicReach><gtr:id>665BC74D-F6C7-4751-9559-7C46F7727EE4</gtr:id><gtr:impact>This work has affected decisions on operation of the national soil monitoring scheme in France and soil monitoring practice in Queensland Australia. The copula methodology has been used to examine options for monitoring contaminants in urban soils of New South Wales and is currently being applied in studies on groundwater time series for important aquifers in the UK.</gtr:impact><gtr:outcomeId>54648d3ab6e276.51621640</gtr:outcomeId><gtr:type>Influenced training of practitioners or researchers</gtr:type></gtr:policyInfluenceOutput></gtr:policyInfluenceOutputs><gtr:productOutputs/><gtr:researchDatabaseAndModelOutputs/><gtr:researchMaterialOutputs/><gtr:softwareAndTechnicalProductOutputs/><gtr:spin